Deep Brain Stimulation

Deepbrain stimulation (DBS) is a neurosurgical procedure that allows targetedcircuit-basedneuromodulationand is commonly used for the treatment ofmovement disorders suchas:

  • Parkinson’s disease
  • Essential tremor
  • Dystonia
  • Epilepsy

In addition, these neuropsychiatric disorders may also benefit from DBS:

  • Tourette’s syndrome
  • Obsessive compulsive disorder
  • Intractable Depression

Parkinson’s Disease (PD)

  • Aneurodegenerative disease clinically manifested by tremor, rigidity, bradykinesiaand postural instability.Itis the most common movement disorder in middle or laterpart of life with a prevalence of about 0.3% of the general population.
  • Pathologicalfindings in Parkinson’s disease are greatly diminishedneuromelaninpigmented neurons in the substantianigrawith associated gliosis, andLewybodiespresent in many neurons.
  • Aloss of dopaminergic neurons in the substantianigraleads to excessiveactivity inthe STN and theGPi. This leads to an exaggerated beta (10-30 Hz)synchronisationwithin and between structures in the basal ganglia circuitry thatcould contributetorigidity andakinesia.
  • Medical therapies(levodopa)increase theavailability of striatal dopamine andtypically result in a brisk symptomatic improvement in most PDpatients.
  • l-DOPAis theprecursorto theneurotransmitterdopamine
  • Unfortunately,the effectiveness of levodopa diminishes over time. Levodopa-induceddyskinesiasandmotorfluctuations developina majority ofpatients after 5+years.

PD-DBS candidates and mobility

Hickey, P. and M. Stacy,Deep Brain Stimulation: A Paradigm Shifting Approach to Treat Parkinson's Disease. Frontiers in Neuroscience, 2016.10(173).

In advanced Parkinson’s disease, the response to levodopa becomesprogressively shorter-> OFF periods and dyskinesia (involuntary movements).

The goal of DBS surgery is to reduce the duration and severity of OFF periods, aswell as an improvement in dyskinesia.

Most patients will continue to take medication after surgery.

DBS Surgical Targets

Common targets for PD include

Internal segment of theGlobuspallidus(GPi)

    • Improves rigidity & tremor
    • Lower chance of cognitivedecline

Subthalamicnucleus (STN)

    • Improves rigidity & tremor
    • ‘Easier’ surgical target
    • Reduction in levodopa dose

Pedunculopontinenucleus (PPN)

    • Can improvepostural stability& gait

DBS Surgical Target-STN

ChoZ-H, Min H-K, Oh S-H, et al. Direct visualization of deep brain stimulation targets in Parkinson disease with the use of 7-teslamagneticresonance imaging: Clinical article.Journal of Neurosurgery JNS 2010;113:639-647.

Surgical Approach

MRI scan visualises the location ofthesubthalamicnucleus (STN).

CT scan visualises a stereotacticframe affixed to patient head.

Co-registered MRI + CT allowsplanning of surgical approach toreach target STN.

Surgeon uses calibrated micro-driveto insert micro-electrode to the STNbeyond (substantianigra,SNr).

Audio recordings of micro-electroderecordings allow confirmation ofarrival at target.

Post-operative imaging

Image shows the electrodes in the STN and connectors at the skull surface.

Extension leads run down the neck to a pair ofImplantable Pulse Generators(IPG) in the chest cavity.

After recovery, a clinician sets stimulation levels.

Mechanism of Action

STN-DBS:

  • Decreases efferentexcitation toSNr
  • Decreases efferentexcitation toGPi
  • Balances inhibitionof Thalamus, viaGPiand directly
  • Balances efferentexcitation toMotor cortex
  • Sometimesreferred to as a‘virtual lesion’mechanism

Avoiding side-effects

Journal of Neural Engineering, 2018.15(5).

segmented electrodes

Possible side effects of DBS:Muscle spasm/twitch,paresthesia(skin tingling),gaze deviation, confusion,hypophonia(soft speech),dysarthria (speech/swallow), depression, aggression,sadness, suicidal ideations, decreased word fluency

Segmented electrodes:Electrode segments allow ‘steering’ of currenttowards relevant anatomy & away from side-effects

Improvements to DBS technology

Cagnan, H., et al.,Emerging technologies for improved deep brain stimulation. Nature Biotechnology, 2019.37(9): p. 1024-1033.

LFP recordings:

  • Alpha/Beta/Gamma

Corticalrecordings:

  • Motor cortex
  • Sensory cortex

Peripheral sensors:

  • Motion sensors
  • Gait/Balancesensors

Closed-loop systems are highly desirable:

  • Facilitate device programming and telehealth
  • Adapt stimulation to disease-state andsymptoms
    • e.g. alpha/beta/gamma activity correlates withtremor/bradykinesia/dyskinesia
